column79: Male Chorus continued until the very first hatchlings are heard. So onset of incubation could not be estimated using Male Chorus. Assuming about 11days for incubation, and hatching day for colony of 4/15, estimate would be 4/5.

column76:
The ARU didn't pick up the colony very well and all vocalizations are quite faint. Female Chatter is never heard, but there is almost continuous Male Chorus, and I can barely hear the young. Fledgling Begging Calls, being more strident, were picked up by the ARUs, and analysis of the Fledgling Begging Calls suggests there were two successful bouts of breeding, with the first bout starting with a small group which then had a larger Addition. This lead to the presence of Fledling Begging Calls from 1-May to 6-May (weak first bout), 22-May to 5-Jun (stronger Addition), and 21-Jun tp 24-Jun (Repeat). If this is correct, I can estimate the breeding stages as Bout #1: Incubation started ~6-Apr, Brooding ~16-Apr, and confirmed to have Fledged on 1-May and Dispersed 6-May. There was an addition to this first bout, with this addition starting to Incubate ~28-Apr, Brooding ~8-May, and was confirmed to have Fledged on 22-May and these fledglings hung around until 5-Jun. Once this first bout was completed, a Repeat bout was initiated and Incubation began ~27-May, Brooding ~7-Jun, and Fledging on 21-Jun and stuck around until 24-Jun, after which the majority of the Fledgling Begging Calls cease. There is a long tail of occasional Fledgling Begging Calls that extends through 27-Jul. I do not know if these are stragglers finishing up a really late breeding attempt, or if these are just fledglings that are re-visiting the area occasionally. Mini Manual was completed. 

ISSUE #1: None of the other results that I've reviewed are explicit about restating the dates like this. There's Table 4 in Results that have all the same information. It seems like either all of the sites should have this restated, or none should. 
ISSUE #2: The dates here are different than what's in Table 4. e.g. Table 4 has FBC from 24-May to 5-Jun, above it says 22-May to 5-Jun. Above says Incubation started 6-Apr, 28-Apr, and 27-May, but the table says Before, ND, and ND.

Some alternate wording for the first part: 
The ARU captured the colony poorly, and all vocalizations were faint. Female Chatter never occurred in the recordings, but Male Chorus was nearly continuous, and only faint vocalizations from young were audible. Fledgling Begging Calls, being more strident, carried into the recordings, and their timing suggests two successful bouts of breeding. The first bout began with a small group that was followed by a larger Addition.

column79: The recorder didn't pick up the colony very well and all vocalizations are quite faint. FS is never heard, but there is almost continuous chorus, and I can hear the young. I am betting that the young hatch multiple days before I pick them up on the recording. Analysis of the Fledgling Calls suggests there were two successful pulses, with the first pulse starting with a small group and then a larger sub-colony addition. This lead to a Fledling call from 5/1-5/6, 5/22-6/5, and 6/21-6/24. I can estimate the breeding stages as Pulse #1: There was a pulse that started incubating ~4/6, hatched ~4/16, and confirmed to have fledged on 5/1 - and these fledglings hung around for about until 5/6, so hung out for a total of 6 days. Since the recorder was placed on 4/14 I am unable to document the onset of incubation. Hatchlings are too far away to hear until they get a few days old. First nestlings are heard on  There was a sub-colony addition to this first pulse, with this addition starting incubation ~4/28, hatching ~5/8, and was confirmed to have fledged on 5/22 and these fledglings hung around until 6/5, or 15 days. When marking MC - looked for SOLID bands just above and below 2kHz, because of the distance of the chorusing at times, it looks underwhelming compared to other recordings which have Male Song at a closer distance, but they were not a SOLID band. Pulse #2: Once this first pulse was completed, a Replacement Pulse was initiated and incubation began ~5/27, hatching ~6/7, and this pulse fledged on 6/21 and stuck around until 6/24 for a total of 4 days, when the majority of the fledgling calls cease. There is a long tail of occasional fledgling calls that extends through 7/27. I do not know if these are stragglers finishing up a really late breeding attempt, or if these are just fledglings that are re-visiting the area occasionally. Mini Manual was completed.

column76: This was a small Asynchronous colony. There are some really young Hatchling Begging Calls heard starting on 14-May that imply that there might be a Repeating bout of breeding, though there is a scattering of Hatchling Begging Calls just prior to this, consistent with an Asynchrounous colony. Female Chatter never took a break and the started up again, again consistent with an Asynchronous breeding colony, rather than a Repeating. The bulk of the breeding was finished by the end of the month and the fledglings Dispersed. It is unknown if the handful of late hatchings survived to fledging as the ARU was pulled after the bulk of the colony Dispersed.
column77: This was a small, primarily Asynchronous colony. Hatchling Begging Calls were first heard on 14 May, with scattered earlier detections also consistent with asynchrony. Female Chatter was continuous without a clear break, further supporting Asynchronous breeding. Most breeding concluded by the end of May, with fledglings dispersing soon after. A few late hatchings may not have fledged, as the ARU was removed after most birds dispersed.
column79: This was a small asynchronous colony. There are some really young nestlngs heard starting on 14-May that imply that there might be a Replacement bout of breeding, though there are no Female Chatter associated with it. Since I hear some Female Chatter all the way through 4-May I suspect that I am just hearing the "dribbles" from the late nesters. Female Chatter never took a break and the started up again, so in this way it acts more like a Continuously breeding colony, rather than a Replacement. And Female Chatter was a continuous decline from onset of Brooding through 4-May. If the hatchlings I hear on 14-May are from the females that are chattering on 2-May it would make them only a couple of days old. The bulk of the breeding was finished by the end of the month and the fledglings dispersed. It is unknown if the handful of late hatchings survived to fledging.

column76: This was a small colony and detection of the infrequent vocalizations is spotty. Only a handful of Nestling Begging Calls are detected, and there is a period of time with no Nestling Begging Calls. column76:
This colony had a Complex form of breeding and exhibited both Addition and Repeating forms. After the first set of birds commenced Brooding, there was an Addition on 4-May. These new arrivals would have occupied new nesting sites, as the first set of individuals were still Brooding. There was a third bout of Male Chorus that occurs approximately at the time the first Fledgling Begging Calls from the first set of birds are heard, that suggest a Repeating bout of breeding by the very first set of birds. This birds from the Addition also had a Repeating bout of breeding and Hatchling Begging Calls are seen for a fourth time. The ARU was collected before this last set of birds would have fledged.

ISSUE: "Repeating" should be "Multiple"?
column77: This colony had a Complex breeding form, with both Addition and Multiple bouts. After the first set of birds began Brooding, an Addition occurred on 4 May. A third Male Chorus coincided with the first fledgling calls, suggesting a Multiple bout by the earliest breeders. Birds from the Addition also appeared to attempt a Multiple bout, as Hatchling Begging Calls were recorded a fourth time. The ARU was collected before this final group could fledge.
column79: This colony had a Complex form of breeding and exhibited both Sub-colony Addition and Replacement forms. After the first bout of breeding commenced Brooding, there was a Sub-colony Addition on 4-May. These new arrivals would have occupied new nesting sites, as the original individuals that formed the colony were still brooding, and thus nests were occupied. In addition, there was a third bout of Male Chorus that occurs approximately at the time the first Fledgling Begging Calls are heard, that suggest that this is a Replacement bout of breeding where the nesting sites previously occupied are reused for another bout of breeding. This Replacement bout is much smaller than the original bout of breeding, and there are only a handful of Female Chatter in June, and only a few Hatchling Begging Calls in June as well. This second weak bout might have also shown a replacement for the sub-colony addition, though it was hard to document, as it was obscured by the vocalizations from the overlapping, and much larger bout of breeding from the first bout, but the presence of Fledgling Begging Calls into mid-June imply that this Replacement bout of at the orignal nesting sites, was also successful. Additionally, there is evidence that there was a Replacement bout of breeding at the Sub-colony Addition sites in that there are hatchlings heard on June 13, which is 28 days after the hatchlings from the first subcolony addition are heard. NOTE - SHOULD ADD THE BLACK ARROWS FOR EACH OF THE HATCHLING BOUTS ONTO THE CHART.

column76: This ARU did not pick up the colony well, and the vocalizations are quite weak. There is evidence of a Repeating bout of breeding, though there are very few vocalizations detected, and if there was Repeating breeding it appears to have been extremely small. The ARU was collected before any young from this second, extremely small bout would have fledged, and the outcome is unknown.

By the time the ARU was placed it appears that the site failed to form a colony, and she reported in the audio clip, taken on the day of deployment, that she only saw one male TRBL. Audio analysis is consistent with her in-person visits.

There were about 100 birds; some of them were carrying nesting material in their beaks". Only one TRBL seen at time of deployment (audio recording 4/29/2021 10:28). When I deployed, there were over 100 trikes, but by the second visit they had decamped and only a dozen remained, then finally only one lonely male who was getting chased off the marsh by RWBBs."

column83: Site is an approx. 4500 sq. meter (1.2 acre) stock pond within a ~400 acre grassland matrix that also hosts CA red-legged frog, CA tiger salamander, and seasonal waterfowl. Surrounding land uses are ranching and horse boarding. There is a shooting range nearby (you may hear shots). I noted about 100 TCBL at the pond April 12. Unfortunately when I returned to place the recorder, they appear to have been supplanted by RWBL. I observed one male TCBL that was chased off the pond by a male RWBL a few times.  I hope the TCBL return!

column83: The Panoche Creek Marsh consists of six miles of brackish perennial surface water, originating in the western part of Silver Creek Ranch, and flowing for about 6 miles through the Preserve and adjacent BLM land, before disappearing into the sandy soils on the western edge of the San Joaquin Valley. The first mile of this wetland consists of a narrow stream which flows through riparian woodland dominated by phreatophytic plants including Fremont cottonwood (Populus fremontii) and red willow (Salix laevigata), and herbaceous understory plants such as salt grass (Distichlis spicata) and alkali heath (Frankenia salina). The stream then broadens into an emergent marsh dominated by narrow-leaf cattail (Typha angustifolia) and bulrush (Schoenoplectus americanus). The TRBL colonies in 2021 occurred primarily along the western half of this wetland. A prescribed burn was conducted in this area on February 7th, 2020.

column76: Three ARUs were placed in this colony. This ARU appears to be a little distant to where the TRBLs are, but I can her the vocalizations. There was also a large Ibis colony that was very loud, which complicated the analysis. Many of the TRBL vocalizations are too faint for template analysis, especially Female Chatter and Hatchling Begging Call, so a mini manual analysis was performed. There were lots of nestlings/fledglings up until about 7-Jul, after which just a few vocalizations detected. Interestingly 7-Jul is the date that the other two colonies in the area dispersed. I suspect that the birds near this ARU were a late attempt compared to the rest of the colony , and that the majority of the nestlings/fledglings were old enough to join the crowd when the rest of the colony left the area.
column79: Manually analyzed data. Large Ibis colony very loud. Recorder appears to be a little distant to where the TRBLs are, but I can her the vocalizations. Many are too faint for template analysis, so a mini manual, followed by edge analysis was performed. Recorder was placed after settlement. Somewhere around when they fail you can hear what I believe might be the other part of the colony right as they are about to fledge. I also think I hear a lot of EUST around this time. There were lots of nestlings up until about 7/6-7/7. Then there is just one or two that hang on. I am calling it a failure at the 7/7ish date. Interestingly this is the date that the other two colonies fledged. My take is that this area was a late attempt compared to the other two areas. And that the majority of the nestlings were old enough to join the crowd when the rest of the colony left the area. Template worked marginally for MS and NC and did not work at all for FS.FS couldn't be located using template analysis. Did mark presence of Female Song when reviewing recordings, so last date here is from these manually reviewed recordings. Recorder was placed just before hatching date, so no Male Chorus. Manual analysis.

column79: Something about these vocalizations sounds different to me, suggesting that in addition to the MS sounding different in this population, so does the Nestling calls. One recorder has it at 17 sec and the other at 27 sec, so if these are in sync at all, the two recorders are approximately 10X343m apart, or 3,430 meters apart, soooo.... Bad news for triangulation they are not in sync at the seconds level. Fledgling dispersal was calculated by scanning thumbnails for a drop in consistent nestling chorus. column76: In-person visits noted that the colony was present and very active on 15-May and by 17-May were quiet, indicating that Incubation had begun. The ARU was placed on 21-May. There is a Fledgling Begging Call right at the very beginning. I suspect that the birds nesting here previously bred elsewhere, and this fledgling is traveling with the colony at the new location. Also, there is another specie's nestling making begging calls right at about the time of TRBL hatching that is more repetitive and lower pitched, which could easily be mistaken for TRBL. I have makred a few of these with the tag non-TRBL.
column79: Recorder was placed after the start of incubation. Based on in-person observations it is believed that they started incubating on 5/17. It was noted that they noticed the colony on 5/15 and by 5/17 were quiet. Recorder was placed 5/21. I am hearing a Fledgling or a few fledglings on 5/26. Could this be from a smaller and earlier nesting attempt, or could it be that a Fledgling has accompanied the flock to this new site. This is a small colony, what happens when there is such a small breeding attempt that the fledglings don't have a good "creche to join? Do they stick with the adults? Rather than forming a creche and leaving the adults? Could this be a RWBL Fledgling? I'm not certain as to what they sound like.

column76: Three ARUs were placed at different locations within a spread out colony. From Ben's notes it appears that the majority of the colony was located near the East ARU, and that the West was expected to have little to no successful breeding. The East location had a single pulse with a faint tail indicating a few asynchronous nests, which is consistent with the fact that Female Chatter was heard seven days past the the date hatchlings were first heard.

column88: Email from Ben on 2/8/2025: "I attached a photo of the "Dollar Marsh" area where TRBL nested in 2024. This area remains the largest stronghold of cattails along the PVP portion of Panoche Creek. When I deployed the AMs, TRBL were well distributed among the cattails throughout this entire area. As nesting began in earnest, it appeared most of the birds(1000-1500) were concentrated in the area directly surrounding AM#42-EAST. There was another group(several hundred) across the marsh adjacent to AM#06-SOUTH. The TRBL using the patchy cattails south of AM#26WEST did not stick around as I thought they might, and I have little hope they were able to successfully nest in that area."

column76: There were two bouts of Male Chorus detected, with the first bout being followed by Female Chatter, indicating a bout of Incubation. Approximately 26 days after the cessation of Male Chorus, the first Fledgling Begging Calls are heard, which correlates perfectly with the expected date if Incubation started just after the cessation of the first bout of Male Chorus (31-May). Onset of the second bout of Male Chorus coincides with the expected onset of Brooding (12-Jun). I have noted that many colonies have a burst of Male Chorus right at onset of Brooding.

column76: The ARU was installed after the onset of Incubation, and during installation, the much larger neighboring group in T27-1 began to arrive and settle. This colony at T27-2 was estimated to be only about 60 adults, resulting in the production of much fewer vocalizations. To increase the number of detections both a manual analysis and a pattern matching analysis were performed. Each method only found a few recordings with vocalizations. Because of the lack of detection, estimating the dates of breeding phases is only approximate. Hatchling Begging Calls are detected on 28-May and a Fledgling Begging Call was detected 14-Jun, indicating successful fledging. NOTE - I have detailed notes from regular site visits.

column76: Male Song and Male Chorus were easily detected, but only a handful of Female Chatter and no Begging Calls were detected using pattern matching, therefore a mini-manual analysis was performed to confirm the pattern matching results. column76: Pattern matching gave robust results. The detection of Fledgling Begging Calls in mid-July is likely from fledglings from the adjacent colony at T27.2 which had fledglings on these dates. There are 219 recordings (11-July to 20-Jul) with Fledgling Begging Calls detected that are from T27.2 fledglings and 39 recordings (26-Jul to 31-Jul) that are from the nesting attempt at this location (T27.1). Since the brightness of the graphs are represent the relative abundance of detections per day, the Fledgling Begging Calls from this colony are very light on the graph. This difference in abundance also indicates that the nesting attempt at T27.2 was much larger than the later nesting attempt at this location. The dates of breeding phases are consistent with the adults from T27.2 undertaking a second nesting attempt at T27.1.
column79: It appears that a few fledglings from T27.1 are heard here in T27.1 just after they fledged, confusing analysis. These older birds are not the end of an earlier pulse in T27.1 because there is no evidence of Female Chatter, YNC, or MNC at all in the recordings evn though the recorder was placed with sufficient time to capture these vocalizations if they had been there. Therefore, I am only documenting a single pulse at this location, though because the ON from the other location are around, I need to document this as p2 to tease the two sets of nestlings apart. Additionally, there may be straggler p1 nestlings in the recordings as well, as they don't quite sound like fledglings to me in all of the recordings where I hear ONC when I "shouldn't". Interestingly, I believe that the birds from T27.2 have shifted their second attempt to T27.1 rather than do a replacement pulse in T27.2 and reusing previous nesting areas, thus the marking as p2 would be appropriate. The number of breeding birds is tiny in this pulse. By the end there are just a few straggling nestlings that can be heard to the end of the recordings. I did manage to document at least one fledgling on 7/27/2023 making the Fledgling calls, and I marked these as Simple Call 2 Present. Many of these calls are starting to take on the Flight-call "yip" sound, but their sonograms are much fuzzier and haven't quite developed the crisp sonogram that the adults have. For making summary excel this "second" pulse has been placed in the "first pulse" slot.

column76: There are lots of vocalizations of a typical colony until 13-Jun when the "keet" Song-Flight Announcement increases. This vocalization is often associated with situations of alarm. There is also a helicopter that shows up in the recordings about this time. A striking example recording is CNWRT27.1am-2024-06-13_12-00.WAV. This also coincides with onset of Brooding (11-Jun). Shortly after this, there are only a handful of reordings with any TRBL vocalizations indicating Partial Abandonment. While there are not many Nestling Begging Calls, they do extend long enough (28-Jun) that the nestlings should have fledged, however Fledgling Begging Calls were never detected. I have seen this lack of Fledgling Begging Calls at other small colonies, and suspect that Fledglings immediately Dispersed.

column76:
The ARU was an LG phone running Arbimon software. Recordings made using these devices resulted in faint sonograms, and pattern matching algorithms do not work well. However, manual analysis of the recordings allowed for detection of vocalizations. Though no Female Chatter was detected using pattern matching analysis, a few instances were located when manually analyzing the recordings. The presence of Female Chatter indicate that females were recruited to the site and had begun nest building. However, five days after the ARU was placed nearly all TRBL vocalizations had ceased and only intermittent Male Song was detected after this date, indicating that the site had been abandoned. A potential cause for the abandonment was the site had active construction of a housing development adjacent to the colony.

ALTERNATE: The ARU was an LG phone running Arbimon software [[version?]]. Due to poor long-range microphone sensitivity of these phones, the recordings had low amplitude and produced faint sonograms, which are too faint to be analyzed by pattern-matching algorithms. While no Female Chatter was identified through automated analysis, several instances were detected manually. The presence of Female Chatter indicates that females were recruited to the site and had begun nest building. However, within five days of ARU deployment, nearly all TRBL vocalizations had ceased, and only intermittent Male Song was recorded thereafter, suggesting colony abandonment. A likely cause of abandonment was ongoing construction of a housing development adjacent to the colony.
column83: The Iron Point colony site is adjacent to Iron Point Road within the city of Folsom, Sacramento County, California (38.647, −121.104) at 172-m elevation. Tricolored blackbirds nested in a 0.2-ha patch of Himalayan blackberry in a small area designated as open space surrounded by roadways, commercial stores, parking lots, and a housing development (Figure 4C). Commercial and residential construction occurred within 80 m of the nesting site in 2018, and construction activities continued during the breeding period.

column76: Pattern Matching analysis of Nestling and Fledgling Begging Calls show an Asynchronous pattern, where Female Pattern shows a Multiple breeding pattern. This appears to be a complex site that largely had Asynchronous breeding but also with a small number of birds undergo a Multiple second breeding bout at the end of May. column76: This colony exhibited both Asynchronous and Multiple breeding forms. The first nesting attempt was Asynchronous. Evidence for Asynchronous breeding include Male Chorus continuing throughout Incubation, Female Chatter extending for 12 days after first Hatchling Begging Calls are heard, and a long tail for the Fledgling Begging Calls. Approximately when the fledglings from this first Asynchronous nesting attempt Disperse there is a second synchronous nesting attempt. Based on the density of vocalizations this second synchronous nesting attempt was much smaller than the first.
column79: This was a highly asynchronous colony. Based on what I hear I believe this was one with a continual expansion/egg laying in each pulse rather than a sub-colony addition. The asynchrony made it challenging to determine MC for pulse 2 asn well as HD for pulse 2. For MC2 I looked for signs of MS at just above Khz 2, and have put a p2c tag at where this band is for many of the recordings. For HD2 I relyed on PMJs to locate recordings with signals of very young nestlings. I then focused on these dates and zoomed in so 8-0 Ktz and about 4 sec were showing on the sonogram. I then looked visually for the signature of very young nestings. It was too hard to try and use my ears to decide if it was a very young nestling or a late nesting from pulse 1.

column76: There was a first attempt that was Partially Abandoned. Partially Abandoned was assigned because the level of activity extremely high and then dramatically drops on 25-Apr, but a handful of Fledgling Begging Calls are detected in late May and early June. Possible causes for the Partial Abandonment include wild pigs, coyotes, and a storm on 3-4 May. The wild pigs were documented as invading the nesting substrate as early as 1-Apr at which time they were reported as “crashing around” within the nesting substrate. On 16-Apr it was reported that the pigs were removed and around 500 TRBL were present, but a coyote was seen. There was concern that the pigs might have created access tunnels for the coyotes and thus possible predation by the coyotes. Female Chatter is detected starting 16-Apr and continues through 27-Apr and then ceases. A visit on 29-Apr notes only about 50 TRBLs, a handful of which were females carrying food. Based on the lack of robust Female Chatter in this first nesting attempt, it appears very few females were recruited to undergo a nesting attempt, and the majority of the birds Abandon. The Retry attempt was successful. Ideally this data set would be analyzed for the presence of TRBL alarm calls as well as audio that indicates pig or coyote. CONSIDER DOING A MANUAL ANALYSIS FROM 15-APR THROUGH 15-MAY TO SEE IF MORE INSIGHTS CAN BE GAINED.

column76: The ARU was an LG phone running Arbimon software. Recordings made using these devices resulted in faint sonograms, and many are barely usable, and pattern matching algorithms did not work well. Manual analysis of the recordings allowed for detection of vocalizations.This ARU was placed west of the 2018 Markham Ravine Main ARU, and the very first recordings have Nestling Begging Calls and Fledgling Begging Calls indicating it was placed during the Fledgling stage and the Fledglings dispersed around 6-Jul. On 7-Jul a second bout of Nestling Begging Calls are detected and continue through the end of the recordings, indicating a Multiple breeding form. The timing of these calls is similar to those found at the 2018 Markham Ravine Main ARU recordings, and are potentially these two sites should be considered part of the same colony. The presence of Fledgling Begging Calls indicating that breeding was successful.

column76: What started out as a strong Male Chorus ended up with very few birds completng the cycle. On 4-June most of the birds have left. This coincides with a bout of temperatures exceeding 90F. It has been noted by Bob that temperatures in this range during incubation and onset of brooding can often lead to abandonment. That said, there is at least one fledgling that survived. Because of the fact that most birds left, there are only a handful of vocalizations detected making the estimate of the timing of the breeding phases only approximate. There is also a few Fledgling Begging Calls prior to the Hatching Begging Calls. This could be a bird from an earlier bout of breeding that is traveling with the adults.

Because I have recordings that span more than 14 days, it appears that these young successfully fledged, though no fledgling calls were detected. Likewise, the second nesting attempt onset of Brooding is likely a few days earlier than when I first detect Hatchling Begging Calls. Nestling Begging Calls are heard for about nine days before there is a dramatic drop in the number of detections. Because I likely missed the first days of Hatchling Begging Calls, it is assumed that this second nesting attempt also successfully fledged on this date and dispersed without being detected on the recordings.

column79: This data set needs a complete relook now that I have my head wrapped around subcolony additions, constant nesting, etc. Look at all of the graphs and really rethink what makes up a pulse. Asynchronous colony that had hints of pulses. Tried my best to document the rough dates of these pulses. Since the colony is aysnchronous these are very rough. After initial Male chorus, there is a scattering of male chorus later in the season, these are marked in the mini-manual analysis and I marked p2c and p3c as best I could to capture these. These other pulses are not as sustained as the first, and female song continues throughout this time. So while there may be other pulses within this colony, but they are not clearly definged. Nestling heard at the end, I think it is not a TRBL, I tagged them as "other nestling" and validated as TRBL nestling call not present. This other nestling has a doublet calls, and it seems less fuzzy and more compact than the TRBL nestling call. Might need to review these all again more carefully. I attempted to mark the 3 pulses even though the dates are a bit blurry due to overlapping pulses and lack of synchrony. The first pulse is smaller than the second, and the fledgling chorus is barely mutliple ONC, but I think I have it right. For feldgling/simple call 2 I am marking the dates with the louder full kHtz calls. UPDATE: By adding the Fledgling Call I think I have this teased out well. I expanded the MC, and can see the three bouts. The 2nd bout of Fledglings is quite brief, existing for really only 5/30. Brian noted colony size in email on Aug 23, 2022.

I have one recording with YNC on 5/16/2022 and there is also a weak FS bout that correlates with this as well as a couple of FCs that imply a fledging date od 5/30. So I am betting that there was actually pulse 1 with hatch day before 5/16 and that these young fledged somewhere around/before 5/30. And there is a second round hatching around 5/27 and these would have fledged after the recordngs stopped. If this is the case, then this suggests a sub colony addition. column76: There are two nesting attempts with the second nesting attempt starting about 23 days after the first. The second nesting attempt in a colony undergoing Multiple nesting attempts is typically more than 28 days after the onset of the first nesting attempt, and commencing when the fledglings have left. This particular case is unusual, in that it is significantly shorter than the 28 day spacing, and likely nestlings are still in the nest from the first wave of breeding. This could be explained if instead of a second nesting attempt, there was a different set of birds that arrived as an Addition which took up unused portions of the breeding substrate. I have field notes for this site collected by Chris Conrad (passed along to me by Deren Ross), and they are consistent an Addition.

column76: Something did not work. Initially the ARU was placed in a plastic baggie, and audio of Male Song can be detected. I then shipped a drybox to them and when the recorder was placed into it the recordings became extremely faint, and unusable. This was the first drybox we used, and we were not aware that it was critical that the microphone be placed near the acoustic membrane. I suspect that the ARU was placed in the drybox in such a way that the microphone was not over the acoustic membrane. Though vocalizations are extemely faint, a mini-manual analysis was able to detect both Male Chorus and Nestling and Fledgling Begging Calls. Based on this, onset of Brooding was ~9-May and since I hear Fledglings, the colony was successful. A complete manual analysis of the site might result in more confident dates and categorization of the colony. I MIGHT BE ABLE TO HAZARD A CALL ON THYPE OF COLONY ONCE I GET GRAPH BACK FROM REDO OF ARBIMON EXCEL.

column76: This colony gets a slow start and then continuously ramps up its breeding effort. There was an first bout of breeding that was either too small or too distant from the recorder to pick up many TRBL vocalizations. This first bout did successfully produce fledglings, and several recordings have Fledgling Begging Calls present on 5/19. I did not locate any recordings prior to this with Hatchling of Nestling Begging Calls. At about a month from the onset of this first weak bout there is a replacement bout that had Continuous breeding that began in the middle of May and it continues into July. This is the bout that I have been able to assign dates as there were plentiful vocalizations.

column76: Male Chorus continued until the first Hatchling Begging Calls were heard, and Female Chatter was heard for 13 days after the first Hatchling Begging Call, indicating an Asynchronous breeding form. In addition to monitoring the colony through audio recordings, volunteers conducted several in-person visits (Table XX). In general, observations made during the visits aligned with the interpretation of breeding stages through analysis of the audio. Of note, volunteers saw fledglings dispersing on the same date that a large drop in Fledgling Begging Calls was identified in the audio analysis, helping to confirm that the sharp drop in Fledgling Begging Calls can be used to estimate dates of creche dispersal.

column79: This was highly asynchronous. The bulk of the nestlings hatch ~4/20ish. I suspect that this is a continuously nesting colony. Because of this I did a manual analysis. Also for MC, I just did three recordings/day every third day. I tagged a scattering of very young nestlings with YNC and older with MNC to show the lack of asynchrony. There might have been something that happened to the recording quality around May 14th in that recordings appear blank. But occassionally I get a recording with something in it, so it could just be a quiet site. UPDATE I went and filled in MC by examining every day from start to end of the first bout. It continues until 4/17. This happens to be 11 days before the last Female Chatter, so I think that there was continuous nesting initiation from until 4/17. Incubation would have been starting from 4/5 and continuously was initiation until 4/17.

column76: Male Chorus continued until a few days after the first hatchlings were heard, and Female Chatter was heard weeks after the first hatchlings were detected, both of which indicate an Asynchronous breeding pattern. Female Chatter was not fully documented, as I confidently identified only 32 vocalizations of this kind throughout the season, instead of a hundred or more that are typically noted. While 2023 followed a similar breeding pattern, I was able to detect more Female Chatter in that year. One notable difference is that in 2023, male chorus ended right as hatchlings were first detected, whereas in 2024, Male Chorus extended well past the detection of the first hatchlings. Thus, in 2024, there was no period lacking Male Chorus or loud Nestling Begging Calls, both of which can drown out the softer Female Chatter.

column76: This site was initially analyzed before pattern matching algorithms were available, and recordings were manually analyzed. Later Pattern Matching analysis was developed and the site was reanalyzed using these new tools. When compared, the two analyses did not agree for the first nesting attempt, and revisiting the manual analysis revealed that there were some errors in my assignment to Hatchling and Nestling Begging Calls. These Begging Calls in early May are from another species. There are a handful of TRBL Hatchling and Fledgling calls May 1-3, but then they stop. So, this first nesting attempt was abandoned. Subsequently, there was a Retry Nesting attempt that started shortly after the Abandonment as well as a third nesting attempt in June. The second and third nesting attempts successfully produced fledglings. Unfortunately for the second nesting attempt in May, there are a few days that coincide with onset of Brooding where the recordings are unusable. Thus, the dates for onset of Brooding in late May are potentially a day or two earlier than reported. NOTE - I have detailed notes from regular site visits.

column83: The Denverton Creek colony site is in a cattle ranch field in Solano County, California, (38.241, −121.888) at 9.0 m elevation. The colony nested in 0.36 ha of Himalayan blackberry Rubus armeniacus in the cattle field and adjacent to Creed Road. Grasslands, grazed by cattle, surround the site. The historical size of the colony is estimated to be 500–2,000 adults. We placed the ARU approximately 125 m from the edge of the colony.

column83: The Hay Landfill colony site is in a mitigation pond adjacent to the Hay Road Landfill in Vacaville, Solano County, California (38.306, −121.825) at 6.5 m elevation. The colony nested in a 7.0-ha, water-managed pond containing Typha spp. covering approximately 25% of the pond. The colony is surrounded by agricultural land and grassland on the eastern, western, and southern borders and a landfill on the northern border. A heavily traveled highway borders the eastern edge.

column76: The first nesting attempt was in the northeast corner of the pond and was about 150m from the ARU, whereas the second nesting attempt was much closer and was in the west part of the pond. There are also a lot of RWBL calls, and the Pattern Matching jobs located these RWBL Female Chatter more readily than the TRBL Female Chatter, as the RWBLs were much closer to the ARU. I was very conservative when annotating the presence of TRBL Female Chatter, and only located 20 of them. There is a small nesting attempt that begins in April, and a handful of Fledgling Begging Calls can be heard on 17-20 May, though no other begging calls were detected, possibly due to the distance from the ARU. A second nesting attempt started in May which was much closer to the ARU and resulted in more detectable Hatchling and Nestling Begging Calls. This second attempt also barely skirted the effects of the strom that was several days before onset of Brooding. NOTE - I have detailed notes from regular site visits.

column76: After the first birds establish a nesting attempt, a larger group joins them about 21 days later, resulting in overlapping breeding stages. Onset of Brooding for the first nesting attempt is roughly determined as the Male Chorus from the Addition drowns out the Hatchling Begging Calls. The fledgling Dispersal date of the first nesting attempt is also an estimate as the Nestling Begging Calls from the Addition make it hard to determine the exact date. Most of the Fledglings from the Addition disperse on 21-Jun, but stragglers can be heard thru the end of the recordings. Battery started running out on 4-Jul and completely died by 13-Jul.

column79: Sub-colony addition. After the first birds established a larger group appears to have joined them, resulting in overlapping breeding stages.  Based on density of nestling calls the second addition of birds was significanly larger than the first. The hatching date for the colony for pulse 1 is estimated, as the onset of pulse 2 Male Chorus drowns out the nestlings. So dates marked as nestling call not present when there is the loud male chorus are likely just because I can't hear them. When I do finally hear them, it is obvious that they are older nestlings. A few nestlings were heard on 5/17, and with most colonies the majority of hatching happens the day after first nestlings are heard, so I estimate that hatching date is ~5/18. The Fledgling dispersal date of pulse 1 is also an estimate as the calls from pulse 2 nestlings make it hard to determine the exact date. For recordings that were analyzed to determine the edge of hatching and dispersal (p1n, p2n) where the two pulaes overlapped I have marked the YNC with the tag YNC-p2 and the older nestling calls with ONC-p1 to distinguish between the two pulses of nestlings. I picked the p1 dispersal date on the day that seemed to have a lull in the ONC. There is a temporary lull in p2 nestling calls 6/12-6/13. There was also a rain storm on that day which maybe explains the lull. The majority of the nestlings disperse on 7/3/2022 (last day with high volume of NCs), but stragglers can be heard thru the end of the recordings. Battery started running out on July 4th and completely died by July 13th.

column76: The first recordings from the ARU have Female Chatter, Fledgling, and Hatchling Begging Calls. Only a few Hatchling Begging Calls were located, but there are many Fledgling Begging Calls. Because of this, I believe that the Fledglings are from an earlier attempt, and that there was an Asynchronous nesting attempt that is the source of the Hatchling Begging Calls.  Because I only have the tail end of the nesting attempt, I do not know the breeding form of the colony, but I suspect Asynchronous because of the Female Chatter and Hatchling Begging Calls that are overlapping the Fledgling Begging Calls. This suggests that both Brooding and Dispersal are occurring simultaneously, consistent with an Asynchronous colony. The Fledglings Dispersed on 31-May, after which only two Fledgling Begging Calls are detected. It is possible that these two Fledgling Begging Calls are coming from the Aysnchonous hatchling heard earlier in the recordings.

In 1999 a bird was detected near this site, and the location has had regular reports most years since. Its unclear if anyone had located this colony prior to my efforts this year, or for how long this actual colony site has been used. It seems they have nested in the area somewhere and somewhat regularly since colonizing Washington.

column88: Audio on 5/27/2022 confirms time and location as Harder Springs. No email notes.

column76: Because Pattern Matching didn't work well, a mini-manual analysis was performed, and when I was still unsatisfied with the results, I reviewed three recordings from every day. The vocalizations I do detect indicate that the nests are located just outside of audio reach for the ARU. I was able to locate a single Female Whine on 2-June, but it is faint. I believe that the two bouts of Fledgling Begging Calls I am detecting are from birds that are forming creches which are occasionally moving closer to the ARU. I detected the first creche starting 17-Jun. Jason reports that there was a colony of ~100 birds at this location and has an account of food carrying on 29-May, which is consistent with Dispersal of around 17-Jun. The second creche I detected starting 27-July.

column79: There were a few recordings with Male Song, and then at the end of the season a fledgling calls can be heard. Because Pattern Matching did'nt work well a mini-manual analysis was performed, and it also failed to detect Female Chatter and nestling calls. Jason reports that there was a colony of ~100 birds at this location and has an account of food carrying on 5/29. I suspect that for some reason the recorder did not pick up the colony very well, and it only registered the louder vocalizations of the Male Song and Fledgling calls, much like Baja this year. I also suspect that the lack of Male Chorus is just due to the small number of birds. Unfortunately, the lack of robust vocalizations make it so I can't tell much from this site. Based on Fledgling call alone a super tentative guess would be Fledging day of 6/17, whch would put hatch day at ~6/3, and incubation start at ~5/23. But this doesn't agree with ebird reports or field visits. Though it is just a few days off. If Food carries on 3/29 (in-person) was the date of hatching, and if on the longer end for fledgling (14days) then date of fledging would be 6/12. Also, with feeding of Fladglings still seen on Aug, this could have been a continuous nesting site. If this was a continuous nesting site, with the small number of birds I would have had an even lower number of vcalizations to pick up, and this might be beyond the reach of my analysis detection abilities. Also of note, this site was much later than the McCain Wetlands and timing suggests that this could be the same birds as at McCain Wetlands but their second bout of breeding.

Also definately some asynchrony - for example :https://arbimon.org/project/tricolored-blackbird-breeding-phenology/visualizer/rec/202905009?a=box,46.88,375,47.2747,21656 has both a fledgling and a young nestling.
column83: Surrounded by wetlands, phragmites, weedy fields, crop, ranchland and shrubsteppe
column87: Jason Fidorra, Wildlife Biologist, Washington Dept of Fish & Wildlife
column88: Audio Moth 31. From audio 3/29/2024 09:31 - no birds were detected at time of deployment. From email "I didn’t see any TRBL at McCain/Othello colony when I got the recorder but I know that I saw over 200 TRBL in the vicinity in April during a drive-by."

column76: Recorder was turned off on 15-May and then turned back on 22-May leading to a gap in audio recordings. This gap is indicated in the figure by ?????. Even with this gap, we are still able to determine onset of Brooding as I was able to manually locate recordings containing Hatchling Begging Calls just prior to the gap.

column79: Recorder was turned off on May 15 and then turned back on on May 22. Luckily we are still able to determine hatch date. There is an odd set of ONC much after fledging day. June 20ish. I suspect this is the roaming band of fledglings that have returned to the area and are hanging out in the habitat.

column76: Nestling and Fledgling Begging Calls were heard on the first day of recordings. It is possible that this is the tail end of a relatively small first nesting attempt, or this could be the middle of an Asynchronous colony. Given the presence of Nestling Begging Calls throughout this time it is most likely an Asynchronous colony
